<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910626-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>910626-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Thermo Electron Corp.:   Energy Systems Subsidiary   Plans Cogeneration Facility</HL><DATE>06/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ED MOB TMO</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)</RE><LP>   Thermo Electron Corp., Waltham, Mass., said itsmajority-owned Thermo Energy Systems unit is developing anelectric-power cogeneration facility on Staten Island, partof New York City, that will cost an estimated $65 million tobuild.   The natural-gas-fueled facility will supply electricity toConsolidated Edison Co., of New York, under a long-termcontract, Thermo Electron said. The facility also will supplysteam to a Mobil Corp. facility. Construction is expected tobegin in mid-1992, the company said.</LP><TEXT>   A Thermo Electron spokesman said the unit plans to sellthe facility and operate it under contract with the buyer; abuyer hasn't been found yet. Alternatively, the subsidiarymay retain ownership of the facility, the spokesman said. &quot;Itwould be a good long-term investment, since we've sold allthe electricity and steam&quot; the facility will produce, hesaid.   Thermo Electron makes analytical instruments, cogenerationsystems, industrial-process equipment, aerospace componentsand other technology products.</TEXT></DOC>